In Trialogus, p. 394, W. hints at a correspondence between the quattuor dotes and the quattuor elementa3 and accepts Anselm’s list of septem. dotes, pulcritudo, velocitas, fortitudo, libertas, sanitas, voluptas et diuturnitas as not inconsistent with the former list, which is as old as Aquinas. These four gifts are also the dower of Christ's mysticat body, Eng. Works, ii. 234.

P. 73, 1. 13.-—Wyclif (Trialogus, p. 238) distinguishes three meanings of scriptura. “Primo scriptura sacra signat J esum Christum librum vitae in quo omnis veritas est inscripta juxta J ohannis x. 35. Secundo modo signat veritates in ipso libro vitae inscriptas, sive sint rationes exemplares aeternae sixe veritates aliae temporales. Et tertio modo famosius quo ad vulgus signat aggregatum ex codicibus legis Dei et ex veritate quarn Deus ipsis imponitfl In Trialogus, p. 244, God Himself is liber vitae. Deus etiam est signum cujuslibet rei signabilis, cum sit liber vitae in quo quodcunque signabile est inscriptum.

P. 73, 1. 13.——-Ziber vitae. In W.'s view here Christ, i.e. the Word containing rationes quotlibet exemplares (supra, p. 12, l. 15). ‘ Every- thing which was created was originally and before its creation in time livingly present, was ideally performed in the eternally pre- existent Logos.’ Lechler, ii. 11.

P. 73, 1. 31.-W. seems to mean that semini tui qni is another instance where change of gender is of doctrina] significance. W. notices below, p. 113, 11. 3-17, Augustine’s attention to grammatical forms. Also p. 184, 1. 22, where W. puts a strain on the text of Augustine.

P. 75, 1. 6.—W.'s theory of Annihilation' was among the ‘earliest heresies' attacked. Fasc. Ziz. 2. Quod Deus non potest annihilare creaturam. Cf. Trial. p. 50.

P. 75, l. 7.—Zibere contradictorie. W. condemns (Trial. p. 72) as a mere scholastic quibble (terminus magistralis erronee introductus) the libertas contradictionis or hypothesis of God's denying himself, i.e. doing otherwise than he has done. Cf. infra, pp. 228, 229.

P. 78, 1. 21.—Donnm. W. adopts from earlier writers this term for the Holy Spirit 3 cf. p. 86, 1. 31.

P. 78, 1. 23. —inconveniens should have been in the text as it is in the passage of Anselm referred to. De Ino. Verbi, V. c. 5. Quoniam ergo quamlibet parvum inconveniens in Deo est impossible, non debuit alia Dei persona incarnari quam Filius. Illo enim incarnato nullum sequitur inconveniens.

P. 79, 1. 9.—Aug. Enchir. c. 36 (Tem. VI. p. 210). Hic omnino granditer et evidenter Dei gratia commendatur. Quid enim natura humana in homine Christo meruit, ut in unitatem personae unici Filii Dei singulariter esset assumpta?

P. 79, l. 30.—W. seems to mean that the Incarnation was necessary for the completion of God’s work in creation. Cf. p. 1, 1. 10, and note.

P. 80, l. 2l.—Pau1iani is the correct name.
